# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: horsepower
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:horsepower/acre-foot] The **acre-foot** is a non-SI unit of volume equal to about 1,233 m3 commonly used in the western United States in reference to large-scale water resources, such as reservoirs, aqueducts, canals, sewer flow capacity, irrigation water, and river flows.
[src:horsepower/acre-foot] An acre-foot equals the volume of water needed to fill approximately an eight-lane swimming pool, 82 ft (25 m) long, 52 ft (16 m) wide and 9.8 ft (3 m) deep.
[src:horsepower/acre-foot] As the name suggests, an acre-foot is defined as the volume of water that would cover one acre of surface area to a depth of one foot.
[src:horsepower/acre-foot] Since an acre is defined as a chain by a furlong (i.e.
[src:horsepower/acre-foot] There have been two definitions of the acre-foot (differing by about 0.0006%), using either the international foot (0.3048 m) or a U.S. survey foot (exactly ⁠1200/3937⁠ meters since 1893).
[src:horsepower/acre-foot] On 31 December 2022, the National Institute of Standards and Technology, the National Geodetic Survey, and the United States Department of Commerce deprecated use of the US survey foot and recommended conversion to either the meter or the international foot.
[src:horsepower/acre-foot] As a rule of thumb in US water management, one acre-foot is taken to be the planned annual water usage of a suburban family household.
[src:horsepower/acre-foot] In some areas of the desert Southwest, where water conservation is followed and often enforced, a typical family uses only about 0.25 acre-feet (310 m3) of water per year.
[src:horsepower/acre-foot] One acre-foot per year is approximately 119.26 cubic feet per day (3.38 cubic meters per day).
[src:horsepower/acre-foot] The **acre-foot per year** has been used historically in the US in many water-management agreements, for example the Colorado River Compact, which divides 15 million acre-feet per year (19 cubic kilometers per year) among seven western US states.
[src:horsepower/acre-foot] Water reservoir capacities in the US are commonly given in **thousands of acre-feet**, abbreviated **TAF** or **KAF**.
[src:horsepower/acre-foot] In most other countries except the US, the metric system is in common use, and water volumes are normally expressed in liters, cubic meters or cubic kilometers.
[src:horsepower/acre-foot] One acre-foot is approximately equivalent to 1.233 megaliters.
[src:horsepower/acre-foot] Large bodies of water may be measured in cubic kilometers (1 km3 equals 1 billion cubic meters or 1,000 gigaliters); 1 million acre-feet approximately equals 1.233 km3.
[src:horsepower/acre-foot] A volumetric change of 10 acre-feet per hour is equivalent to exactly 121 cubic feet per second.
[src:horsepower/acre-foot] Dividing by 120, this reduces to 1 **acre-inch** per hour is approximately 1.01 ft3/s.
[src:horsepower/acre-foot] This can be visualized as such: suppose a 1-acre field is receiving a sustained rainfall of 1 inch per hour.
[src:horsepower/acre-foot] To prevent the field from flooding or overflowing, the drainage system must be able to handle a discharge of at least 1 cubic foot per second.
[src:horsepower/acre] The **acre** (/ˈeɪkər/ *AY-kər*) is a unit of land area used in the British imperial and the United States customary systems.
[src:horsepower/acre] It is traditionally defined as the area of one chain by one furlong (66 by 660 feet), which is exactly equal to 10 square chains, 1⁄640 of a square mile, 4,840 square yards, or 43,560 square feet, and approximately 4,047 m2, or about 40% of a hectare.
[src:horsepower/acre] The acre is sometimes abbreviated **ac**, but is usually spelled out as the word "acre".
[src:horsepower/acre] Traditionally, in the Middle Ages, an acre was conceived of as the area of land that could be ploughed by one man using a team of eight oxen in one day.
[src:horsepower/acre] The acre is still a statutory measure in the United States, where both the international acre and the US survey acre are in use, but they differ by only four parts per million.
[src:horsepower/acre] The most common use of the acre is to measure tracts of land.
[src:horsepower/acre] The acre is used in many existing and former Commonwealth of Nations countries by custom.
[src:horsepower/acre] In a few, it continues as a statute measure, although not since 2010 in the UK, and not for decades in Australia, New Zealand, and South Africa.
[src:horsepower/acre] In many places where the acre is no longer a statute measure, it is still lawful to use as supplementary information next to the statutory hectare measurement.
[src:horsepower/acre] While all modern variants of the acre contain 4,840 square yards, there are alternative definitions of a yard, so the exact size of an acre depends upon the particular yard on which it is based.
[src:horsepower/acre] Originally, an acre was understood as a strip of land sized at forty perches (660 ft, or 1 furlong) long and four perches (66 ft) wide; this may have also been understood as an approximation of the amount of land a yoke of oxen could plough in one day (a furlong being "a furrow long").
[src:horsepower/acre] A square enclosing one acre is approximately 69.57 yards, or 208 feet 9 inches (63.61 metres), on a side.
[src:horsepower/acre] As a unit of measure, an acre has no prescribed shape; any area of 43,560 square feet is an acre.
[src:horsepower/acre] In the international yard and pound agreement of 1959, the United States and five countries of the Commonwealth of Nations defined the international yard to be exactly 0.9144 metre.
[src:horsepower/acre] The US authorities decided that, while the refined definition would apply nationally in all other respects, the US survey foot (and thus the survey acre) would continue 'until such a time as it becomes desirable and expedient to readjust [it]'.
[src:horsepower/acre] By inference, an "international acre" may be calculated as exactly 4,046.8564224 square metres but it does not have a basis in any international agreement.
[src:horsepower/acre] Both the international acre and the US survey acre contain 1⁄640 of a square mile or 4,840 square yards, but alternative definitions of a yard are used (see *Foot (unit) § Survey foot* and *Yard § Conversions*), so the exact size of an acre depends upon the yard upon which it is based.
[src:horsepower/acre] The US survey acre is about 4,046.872 square metres; its exact value (⁠4046+13,525,426/15,499,969⁠ m2) is based on an inch defined by 1 metre = 39.37 inches exactly, as established by the Mendenhall Order of 1893.
[src:horsepower/acre] Surveyors in the United States use both international and survey feet, and consequently, both varieties of acre.
[src:horsepower/acre] Since the difference between the US survey acre and international acre (0.016 square metres, 160 square centimetres or 24.8 square inches), is only about a quarter of the size of an A4 sheet or US letter, it is usually not important which one is being discussed.
[src:horsepower/acre] Areas are seldom measured with sufficient accuracy for the different definitions to be detectable.
[src:horsepower/acre] In October 2019, the US National Geodetic Survey and the National Institute of Standards and Technology announced their joint intent to end the "temporary" continuance of the US survey foot, mile, and acre units (as permitted by their 1959 decision, above), with effect from the end of 2022.
[src:horsepower/acre] The Puerto Rican *cuerda* (0.39 ha; 0.97 acres) is sometimes called the "Spanish acre" in the continental United States.
[src:horsepower/acre] The acre is commonly used in many current and former Commonwealth countries by custom, and in a few it continues as a statute measure.
[src:horsepower/acre] These include Antigua and Barbuda, American Samoa, The Bahamas, Belize, the British Virgin Islands, Canada, the Cayman Islands, Dominica, the Falkland Islands, Grenada, Ghana, Guam, the Northern Mariana Islands, Jamaica, Montserrat, Samoa, Saint Lucia, St.
[src:horsepower/acre] Vincent and the Grenadines, Turks and Caicos, the United Kingdom, the United States, and the US Virgin Islands.
[src:horsepower/acre] In the Republic of Ireland, the hectare is legally used under European units of measurement directives; however, the acre (the same standard statute as used in the UK, not the old Irish acre, which was of a different size) is still widely used, especially in agriculture.
[src:horsepower/acre] In India, residential plots are measured in square feet, square yard or square metre, while agricultural land is measured in bigha, acres or hectare.
[src:horsepower/acre] In Sri Lanka, the division of an acre into 160 perches or 4 roods is common.
[src:horsepower/acre] In Pakistan, residential plots are measured in Kanal (20 *marla* = 1 *kanal* = 605 sq yards) and open/agriculture land measurement is in acres (8 *kanal* = 1 acre) and *muraba* (25 acres = 1 *muraba* = 200 *kanal*), *jerib, wiswa* and *gunta*.
[src:horsepower/acre] Its use as a primary unit for trade in the United Kingdom ceased to be permitted from 1 October 1995, due to the 1994 amendment of the Weights and Measures Act, where it was replaced by the hectare – though its use as a supplementary unit continues to be permitted indefinitely.
[src:horsepower/acre] This was with the exemption of land registration, which records the sale and possession of land; in 2010 HM Land Registry ended its exemption.
[src:horsepower/acre] The measure is still used to communicate with the public, and informally (non-contract) by the farming and property industries.
[src:horsepower/acre] Perhaps the easiest way for US residents to envision an acre is as a rectangle measuring 88 yards by 55 yards (1⁄10 of 880 yards by 1⁄16 of 880 yards), about 9⁄10 the size of a standard American football field.
[src:horsepower/acre] To be more exact, one acre is 90.75% of a 100-yd-long by 53.33-yd-wide American football field (without the end zone).
[src:horsepower/acre] The full field, including the end zones, covers about 1.32 acres (0.53 ha).
[src:horsepower/acre] For residents of other countries, the acre might be envisioned as rather more than half of a 1.76 acres (0.71 ha) football pitch.
[src:horsepower/acre] The word *acre* is derived from the Norman, attested for the first time in 1006 in a text from Fécamp with the meaning of "agrarian measure".
[src:horsepower/acre] In English, an obsolete variant spelling was *aker*.
[src:horsepower/acre] According to the Act on the Composition of Yards and Perches, dating from around 1300, an acre is "40 perches [rods] in length and four in breadth", meaning 220 yards by 22 yards.
[src:horsepower/acre] As detailed in the diagram, an acre was roughly the amount of land tillable by a yoke of oxen in one day.
[src:horsepower/acre] Before the introduction of the metric system, many countries in Europe used their own official "acres" (with other names).
[src:horsepower/acre] In France, the traditional unit of area was the *arpent carré*, a measure based on the Roman system of land measurement.
[src:horsepower/acre] The *acre* was used only in Normandy (and neighbouring places outside its traditional borders), but its value varied greatly across Normandy, ranging from 3,632 to 9,725 square metres, with 8,172 square metres being the most frequent value.
[src:horsepower/acre] But inside the same *pays* of Normandy, for instance in pays de Caux, the farmers (still in the 20th century) made the difference between the *grande acre* (68 ares, 66 centiares) and the *petite acre* (56 to 65 ca).
[src:horsepower/acre] The Normandy *acre* was usually divided in 4 *vergées* (roods) and 160 square *perches*, like the English acre.
[src:horsepower/acre] The Normandy *acre* was equal to 1.6 *arpents*, the unit of area more commonly used in Northern France outside of Normandy.
[src:horsepower/acre] In Germany, the Netherlands, and Eastern Europe the traditional unit of area was *Morgen*.
[src:horsepower/acre] Like the acre, the *morgen* was a unit of ploughland, representing a strip that could be ploughed by one man and an ox or horse in a morning.
[src:horsepower/acre] There were many variants of the *morgen*, differing between the different German territories, ranging from 1⁄2 to 2+1⁄2 acres (2,000 to 10,100 m2).
[src:horsepower/acre] It was also used in Old Prussia, in the Balkans, Norway, and Denmark, where it was equal to about two-thirds acre (2,700 m2).
[src:horsepower/acre] Historically, the size of farms and landed estates in the United Kingdom was usually expressed in acres (or acres, roods, and perches), even if the number of acres was so large that it might conveniently have been expressed in square miles.
[src:horsepower/acre] For example, a certain landowner might have been said to own 32,000 acres of land, not 50 square miles of land.
[src:horsepower/acre] The acre is related to the square mile, with 640 acres making up one square mile.
[src:horsepower/acre] In western Canada and the western United States, divisions of land area were typically based on the square mile, and fractions thereof.
[src:horsepower/acre] If the square mile is divided into quarters, each quarter has a side length of 1⁄2 mile (880 yards) and is 1⁄4 square mile in area, or 160 acres.
[src:horsepower/acre] These subunits are typically then again divided into quarters, with each side being 1⁄4 mile long, and being 1⁄16 of a square mile in area, or 40 acres.
[src:horsepower/acre] In the United States, farmland was typically divided as such, and the phrase "the back 40" refers to the 40-acre parcel to the back of the farm.
[src:horsepower/acre] Most of the Canadian Prairie Provinces and the US Midwest are on square-mile grids for surveying purposes.
[src:horsepower/alam] The **Association of Licensed Automobile Manufacturers** (**ALAM**), began as the **Manufacturer's Mutual Association** (**MMA**), an organization originally formed to challenge the litigation of the fledgling automobile industry by George B.
[src:horsepower/alam] Selden and the Electric Vehicle Company.
[src:horsepower/alam] Ultimately, the organization took advantage of its power and became Selden's greatest ally.
[src:horsepower/alam] In exchange for favorable royalty rates, the group gained the power to litigate and exclude other manufacturers from licensing, making them the most powerful group in the early automotive industry.
[src:horsepower/alam] In 1899, the Electric Vehicle Company purchased the rights to Selden's automobile patent.
[src:horsepower/alam] The patent was deemed flimsy by most of the industry, but the company purchased the rights to guarantee the legality of their new venture, the Columbia Automobile Company.
[src:horsepower/alam] A year later, however, the Columbia Automobile Company was in shambles thanks to internal corruption and low demand for electric vehicles, and the Electric Vehicle Company turned to the Selden patent as an alternative source of revenue.
[src:horsepower/alam] They set out to have manufacturers pay a 5% royalty on all cars produced.
[src:horsepower/alam] By 1900, The Electric Vehicle Company launched several lawsuits against automobile manufacturers.
[src:horsepower/alam] Their ultimate target among the fray was Alexander Winton, and his Winton Motor Carriage Company.
[src:horsepower/alam] Originally formed in 1896, the Winton Company was by 1900 the highest-volume automobile producer in the US.
[src:horsepower/alam] If the patent were to gain validity in the industry, Selden believed, they needed to tackle the largest manufacturer.
[src:horsepower/alam] The Winton Company's defense made the costly mistake of concentrating on challenging the patent’s validity through demurrer; by 1902 the case was still tied up and Winton was considering a settlement.
[src:horsepower/alam] In response to his distress, other independent automobile makers formed a group called the Manufacturers Mutual Association to breathe new life into Winton's legal defense.
[src:horsepower/alam] Formed by Henry Bourne Joy of Packard and Frederic L.
[src:horsepower/alam] Smith of Olds, the two entrepreneurs used their position to threaten the Electric Vehicle Company.
[src:horsepower/alam] The MMA called for much lower royalty payments and for the legal and license rights to be controlled by the MMA, or else they would bolster Winton's dying legal fund.
[src:horsepower/alam] By 1903, the organization had officially become the Association of Licensed Automobile Manufacturers, and had secured favorable rights from the Electric Vehicle Company.
[src:horsepower/alam] Only a few months after the formation of the organization, Winton became an ALAM member, and the suit against his company was dropped.
[src:horsepower/alam] The patent had gained legitimacy without ever having its validity determined.
[src:horsepower/alam] The ALAM gained from the agreement, giving them control over the entire automobile industry for a relatively low cost.
[src:horsepower/alam] The group negotiated a 1.25% royalty on all cars produced, one-half of one percent of which went directly into the ALAM legal and operations funds.
[src:horsepower/alam] Applications for ALAM membership and a Selden license were granted only by the unanimous decision of a five-member executive board.
[src:horsepower/alam] This system left ALAM members with royalties considerably lower than the costs of trying the Selden patent in the courts, and gave existing members the ability to exclude and even litigate unlicensed competitors.
[src:horsepower/alam] The ALAM's exclusionary policies were ultimately its undoing.
[src:horsepower/alam] The up-and-coming Ford Motor Company was capitalized in 1903, and Henry Ford immediately attempted to secure a Selden license.
[src:horsepower/alam] He was denied, officially due to his past business failures (the Detroit Automobile Company and the Henry Ford Company, specifically), and also due to the protectionist climate of the ALAM.
[src:horsepower/alam] Frederic Smith of Olds was the executive board member most outspoken against Ford’s admission to the ALAM, and also had the most to lose from such an admission, as he held most of the Detroit market for mass-produced automobiles.
[src:horsepower/alam] On October 22, 1903, the ALAM filed suit with the Ford Motor Company, and what followed was a messy public relations battle.
[src:horsepower/alam] The ALAM launched a campaign threatening to sue those who purchased Ford automobiles.
[src:horsepower/alam] Ford responded in-kind, summing up their position as, "We believe that the art would have been just as far advanced to-day if Mr.
[src:horsepower/alam] On September 15, 1909, presiding judge Charles Merrill Hough found legitimacy in the Selden patent.
[src:horsepower/alam] The court of appeals later overturned the ruling, finding in favor of Ford on January 9, 1911.
[src:horsepower/alliance-of-automobile-manufacturers] The **Auto Alliance** (**AAM**) is a defunct trade group of automobile manufacturers that operated in the United States.
[src:horsepower/alliance-of-automobile-manufacturers] It was the leading advocacy group for the auto industry, representing 77% of all car and light truck sales in the United States.
[src:horsepower/alliance-of-automobile-manufacturers] The Auto Alliance was active in the areas of environment, energy and motor vehicle safety.
[src:horsepower/alliance-of-automobile-manufacturers] In 2019, the Alliance was merged with the Association of Global Automakers to form the Alliance for Automotive Innovation.
[src:horsepower/alliance-of-automobile-manufacturers] John Bozzella of Global Automakers became the new CEO.
[src:horsepower/alliance-of-automobile-manufacturers] The trade group formed on January 13, 1999, to replace the American Automobile Manufacturers Association, which had represented only American manufacturers.
[src:horsepower/alliance-of-automobile-manufacturers] As an advocacy group for the automobile industry on public policy issues, an example of the alliance's activity includes sponsorship of the Transportation Data Center at the University of Michigan Transportation Research Institute (UMTRI).
[src:horsepower/alliance-of-automobile-manufacturers] Likewise, the alliance was active in political lobbying on behalf of the industry.
[src:horsepower/alliance-of-automobile-manufacturers] The alliance appealed, for instance, a district-court ruling in California in September 2007 that upheld states' ability to regulate exhaust emissions, the issue having a strong bearing on state and federal vehicle mileage regulations.
[src:horsepower/alliance-of-automobile-manufacturers] They also have weighed in on the federal government's new fuel economy and emissions standards proposals calling for other industries to do their part in helping to trim pollution and conserve energy.
[src:horsepower/alliance-of-automobile-manufacturers] The Alliance opposes the Motor Vehicle Owners' Right to Repair Act.
[src:horsepower/alliance-of-automobile-manufacturers] In September 2009, the Alliance of Automobile Manufacturers joined the Obama administration and environmentalists in opposing an effort to bar the U.S.
[src:horsepower/alliance-of-automobile-manufacturers] Environmental Protection Agency for one year from attempting to regulate green-house-gas emissions for power plants and other large sources, preferring a single nationwide set of rules, a main priority since 2002.
[src:horsepower/alliance-of-automobile-manufacturers] AAM suggested to the coming Trump government in November 2016 that the Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) fuel economy rules be reviewed and relaxed.
[src:horsepower/alternator] An **alternator** (or **synchronous generator**) is an electrical generator that converts mechanical energy to electrical energy in the form of alternating current (AC).
[src:horsepower/alternator] For reasons of cost and simplicity, most alternators use a rotating magnetic field with a stationary armature.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The rotor coil is externally excited by a small direct current (DC), while the AC is generated in the stationary coils.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Occasionally, a linear alternator or a rotating armature with a stationary magnetic field is used.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Although any AC electrical generator might be called an alternator, usually the term refers to small rotating machines driven by automotive and other internal combustion engines.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The term usually applies those types with externally excited rotor coils.
[src:horsepower/alternator] An alternator that uses a permanent magnet for its magnetic field is called a magneto.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Alternators in power stations driven by steam turbines are called turbo-alternators.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Large 50 or 60 Hz three-phase alternators in power plants generate most of the world's electric power, which is distributed by electric power grids.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Alternating current generating systems were known in simple forms from the discovery of the magnetic induction of electric current in the 1830s.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Rotating generators naturally produced alternating current, but since there was little use for it, it was normally converted into direct current via the addition of a commutator in the generator.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The early machines were developed by pioneers such as Michael Faraday and Hippolyte Pixii.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Faraday developed the "rotating rectangle", whose operation was *heteropolar* – each active conductor passed successively through regions where the magnetic field was in opposite directions.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Lord Kelvin and Sebastian Ferranti also developed early alternators, producing frequencies between 100 and 300 Hz.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The late 1870s saw the introduction of the first large-scale electrical systems with central generation stations to power Arc lamps, used to light whole streets, factory yards, or the interior of large warehouses.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Some, such as Yablochkov arc lamps introduced in 1878, ran better on alternating current, and the development of these early AC generating systems was accompanied by the first use of the word "alternator".
[src:horsepower/alternator] Supplying the proper amount of voltage from generating stations in these early systems was left up to the engineer's skill in "riding the load".
[src:horsepower/alternator] In 1883 the Ganz Works invented the constant voltage generator that could produce a stated output voltage, regardless of the value of the actual load.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The introduction of transformers in the mid-1880s led to the widespread use of alternating current and the use of alternators needed to produce it.
[src:horsepower/alternator] After 1891, polyphase alternators were introduced to supply currents of multiple differing phases.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Later alternators were designed for various alternating current frequencies between sixteen and about one hundred hertz for use with arc lighting, incandescent lighting, and electric motors.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Specialized radio frequency alternators like the Alexanderson alternator were developed as longwave radio transmitters around World War 1 and used in a few high power wireless telegraphy stations before vacuum tube transmitters replaced them.
[src:horsepower/alternator] A conductor moving relative to a magnetic field develops an electromotive force (EMF) in it (Faraday's Law).
[src:horsepower/alternator] This EMF reverses its polarity when it moves under magnetic poles of opposite polarity.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Typically, a rotating magnet, called the rotor, turns within a stationary set of conductors, called the stator, wound in coils on an iron core.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The field cuts across the conductors, generating an induced EMF (electromotive force), as the mechanical input causes the rotor to turn.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The rotating magnetic field induces an AC voltage in the stator windings.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Since the currents in the stator windings vary in step with the position of the rotor, an alternator is a synchronous generator.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The rotor's magnetic field may be produced by permanent magnets or by a field coil electromagnet.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Automotive alternators use a rotor winding, which allows control of the alternator's generated voltage by varying the current in the rotor field winding.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Permanent magnet machines avoid the loss due to magnetizing current in the rotor, but are restricted in size due to the cost of the magnet material.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Since the permanent magnet field is constant, the terminal voltage varies directly with the speed of the generator.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Brushless AC generators are usually larger than those used in automotive applications.
[src:horsepower/alternator] An automatic voltage control device controls the field current to keep the output voltage constant.
[src:horsepower/alternator] If the output voltage from the stationary armature coils drops due to an increase in demand, more current is fed into the rotating field coils through the voltage regulator (VR).
[src:horsepower/alternator] This increases the magnetic field around the field coils, which induces a greater voltage in the armature coils.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Thus, the output voltage is brought back up to its original value.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Alternators used in central power stations also control the field current to regulate reactive power and to help stabilize the power system against the effects of momentary faults.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Often, there are three sets of stator windings, physically offset so that the rotating magnetic field produces a three-phase current, displaced by one-third of a period with respect to each other.
[src:horsepower/alternator] One cycle of alternating current is produced each time a pair of field poles passes over a point on the stationary winding.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The relation between speed and frequency is $N=120f/P$ , where f is the frequency in Hz (cycles per second).
[src:horsepower/alternator] P is the number of poles (2, 4, 6, ...), and N is the rotational speed in revolutions per minute (r/min).
[src:horsepower/alternator] Old descriptions of alternating current systems sometimes give the frequency in terms of alternations per minute, counting each half-cycle as one *alternation*; so 12,000 alternations per minute corresponds to 100 Hz.
[src:horsepower/alternator] An alternator's output frequency depends on the number of poles and the rotational speed.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The speed corresponding to a particular frequency is called the *synchronous speed*.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Alternators may be classified by the method of excitation, number of phases, the type of rotation, cooling method, and their application.
[src:horsepower/alternator] There are two main ways to produce the magnetic field used in the alternators: by using permanent magnets, which create their persistent magnetic field, or by using field coils.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The alternators that use permanent magnets are specifically called magnetos.
[src:horsepower/alternator] In other alternators, wound field coils form an electromagnet to produce the rotating magnetic field.
[src:horsepower/alternator] A device that uses permanent magnets to produce alternating current is called a permanent magnet alternator (PMA).
[src:horsepower/alternator] A permanent magnet generator (PMG) may produce either alternating current or direct current if it has a commutator.
[src:horsepower/alternator] This method of excitation consists of a smaller direct-current (DC) generator fixed on the same shaft as the alternator.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The DC generator generates a small amount of electricity, just enough to *excite* the field coils of the connected alternator to generate electricity.
[src:horsepower/alternator] A variation of this system is a type of alternator that uses direct current from a battery for initial excitation upon start-up, after which the alternator becomes self-excited.
[src:horsepower/alternator] This method of excitation consists of a smaller alternating-current (AC) generator fixed on the same shaft as the alternator.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The AC stator generates a small amount of field coil excitation current, which is induced in the rotor and rectified to DC by a bridge rectifier built in to the windings where it excites the field coils of the larger connected alternator to generate electricity.
[src:horsepower/alternator] This system has the advantage of not requiring brushes, which increases service life, although with a slightly lower overall efficiency.
[src:horsepower/alternator] This method depends on residual magnetism retained in the iron core to generate a weak magnetic field, which would allow a weak voltage to be generated.
[src:horsepower/alternator] This voltage is used to excite the field coils so the alternator can generate stronger voltage as part of its *build up* process.
[src:horsepower/alternator] After the initial AC voltage buildup, the field is supplied with rectified voltage from the alternator.
[src:horsepower/alternator] A brushless alternator is composed of two alternators built end-to-end on one shaft.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Until 1966, alternators used brushes with rotating field.
[src:horsepower/alternator] With the advancement in semiconductor technology, brushless alternators are possible.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Smaller brushless alternators may look like one unit, but the two parts are readily identifiable in the large versions.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The main alternator is the larger of the two sections, and the smaller one is the exciter.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The exciter has stationary field coils and a rotating armature (power coils).
[src:horsepower/alternator] The main alternator uses the opposite configuration with a rotating field and stationary armature.
[src:horsepower/alternator] A bridge rectifier, called the rotating rectifier assembly, is mounted on the rotor.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Neither brushes nor slip rings are used, which reduces the number of wearing parts.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The main alternator has a rotating field and a stationary armature (power generation windings).
[src:horsepower/alternator] Varying the amount of current through the stationary exciter field coils varies the 3-phase output from the exciter.
[src:horsepower/alternator] This output is rectified by a rotating rectifier assembly mounted on the rotor, and the resultant DC supplies the rotating field of the main alternator and hence alternator output.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The result is that a small DC exciter current indirectly controls the output of the main alternator.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Another way to classify alternators is by the number of phases of their output voltage.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The output can be single-phase or polyphase.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Three-phase alternators are the most common, but polyphase alternators can be two-phase, six-phase, or more.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The revolving part of alternators can be the armature or the magnetic field.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The revolving armature type has the armature wound on the rotor, where the winding moves through a stationary magnetic field.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The revolving armature type is not often used.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The revolving field type has a magnetic field on the rotor to rotate through a stationary armature winding.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The stationary armature can be wound for any convenient medium voltage level, up to tens of thousands of volts; manufacture of slip ring connections for more than a few thousand volts is costly and inconvenient.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Many alternators are cooled by ambient air, forced through the enclosure by an attached fan on the shaft that drives the alternator.
[src:horsepower/alternator] In vehicles such as transit buses, a heavy demand on the electrical system may require a large alternator to be oil-cooled.
[src:horsepower/alternator] In marine applications water-cooling is also used.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Expensive automobiles may use water-cooled alternators to meet high electrical system demands.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Most power generation stations use synchronous machines as their generators.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The connection of these generators to the utility grid requires synchronization conditions to be met.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Synchronous generators provide several important system services.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Their inherent rotational inertia slows the initial frequency decline after a sudden loss of generation, allowing turbine governors and other frequency-control reserves time to respond and restore balance.
[src:horsepower/alternator] This role is increasingly significant as the share of non-synchronous generation, such as solar photovoltaics and many modern wind plants, grows in many power systems.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Alternators are used in modern internal combustion engine automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:horsepower/alternator] With the availability of affordable silicon-diode rectifiers, alternators were used instead.
[src:horsepower/alternator] In later diesel–electric locomotives and diesel–electric multiple units, the prime mover turns an alternator which provides electricity for the traction motors (AC or DC).
[src:horsepower/alternator] The traction alternator usually incorporates integral silicon diode rectifiers to provide the traction motors with up to 1,200 volts DC.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The first diesel electric locomotives, and many of those still in service, use DC generators as, before silicon power electronics, it was easier to control the speed of DC traction motors.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Most of these had two generators: one to generate the excitation current for a larger main generator.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Optionally, the generator also supplies head-end power (HEP) or power for electric train heating.
[src:horsepower/alternator] The HEP option requires a constant engine speed, typically 900 r/min for a 480 V 60 Hz HEP application, even when the locomotive is not moving.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Marine alternators used in yachts are similar to automotive alternators, with appropriate adaptations to the salt-water environment.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Marine alternators are designed to be explosion proof (ignition protected) so that brush sparking will not ignite explosive gas mixtures in an engine room environment.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Depending on the type of system installed, they may be 12 or 24 volts.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Larger marine diesels may have two or more alternators to cope with the heavy electrical demand of a modern yacht.
[src:horsepower/alternator] On single alternator circuits, the power may be split between the engine starting battery and the domestic or house battery (or batteries) by use of a split-charge diode (battery isolator) or a voltage-sensitive relay.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Due to the high cost of large house battery banks, Marine alternators generally use external regulators.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Multistep regulators control the field current to maximize the charging effectiveness (time to charge) and battery life.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Multistep regulators can be programmed for different battery types.
[src:horsepower/alternator] Two temperature sensors can be added: one for the battery to adjust the charging voltage and an over-temperature sensor on the actual alternator to protect it from overheating.
[src:horsepower/alternator] High-frequency alternators of the variable-reluctance type were applied commercially to radio transmission in low-frequency radio bands.
[src:horsepower/alternator] These were used for transmitting Morse code and, experimentally, for transmitting voice and music.
[src:horsepower/alternator] In the Alexanderson alternator, both the field winding and armature winding are stationary, and current is induced in the armature by the changing magnetic reluctance of the rotor (which has no windings or current-carrying parts).
[src:horsepower/alternator] Such machines were made to produce radio frequency current for radio transmissions, although the efficiency was low.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Founded as an engineering society focused on mechanical engineering in North America, ASME is today multidisciplinary and global.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has over 85,000 members in more than 135 countries worldwide.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME was founded in 1880 in response to numerous steam boiler pressure vessel failures by Alexander Lyman Holley, Henry Rossiter Worthington, John Edison Sweet and Matthias N.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Forney, with Robert Henry Thurston as the society's founding president.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Known for setting codes and standards for mechanical devices, ASME conducts one of the world's largest technical publishing operations.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It holds numerous technical conferences and hundreds of professional development courses each year and sponsors numerous outreach and educational programs.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Ned Djilali and Georgia Tech president and woman engineer supporter Blake R Van Leer were executive members.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Kate Gleason and Lydia Weld were the first two women members.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME is one of the oldest standards-developing organizations in America.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It produces approximately 600 codes and standards covering many technical areas, such as fasteners, plumbing fixtures, elevators, pipelines, and power plant systems and components.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are developed by committees of subject matter experts using an open, consensus-based process.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Many ASME standards are cited by government agencies as tools to meet their regulatory objectives.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME standards are therefore voluntary, unless the standards have been incorporated into a legally binding business contract or incorporated into regulations enforced by an authority having jurisdiction, such as a federal, state, or local government agency.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are used in more than 100 countries and have been translated into numerous languages.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The largest ASME standard, both in size and in the number of volunteers involved in its preparation, is the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (BPVC).
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The BPVC provides rules for the design, fabrication, installation, inspection, care, and use of boilers, pressure vessels, and nuclear components.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The code also includes standards on materials, welding and brazing procedures and qualifications, nondestructive examination, and nuclear in-service inspection.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to academic journals, since 1880 the ASME has also published the magazine *Mechanical Engineering*.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] This means the nominees need not be professional educators.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] (1879–1964), an ASME Member and professor of mechanical engineering and head of the department at the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn, established the Medal.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME runs several annual E-Fests, or Engineering Festivals, taking the place of the Student Professional Development Conference (SPDC) series.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to the Human Powered Vehicle Challenge (HPVC), the Innovative Additive Manufacturing 3D Challenge (IAM3D), the Student Design Competition, and the Old Guard Competition, there are also talks, interactive workshops, and entertainment.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] These events allows students to network with working engineers, host contests, and promote ASME's benefits to students as well as professionals.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] E-Fests are held in four regions in the United States and internationally—western U.S, eastern U.S., Asia Pacific, and South America—with the E-Fest location for each region changing every year.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME holds a variety of competitions every year for engineering students from around the world.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has four key offices in the United States, including its headquarters operation in New York, N.Y., and three international offices in Beijing, China; Brussels, Belgium, and New Delhi, India.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has two institutes and 32 technical divisions within its organizational structure.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In 1982, ASME was found to be the first non-profit organization to in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:horsepower/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The United States Supreme Court found the organization liable for more than $6 million in *American Society of Mechanical Engineers v.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] The AWG originated in the number of drawing operations used to produce a given gauge of wire.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] Very fine wire (for example, 30 gauge) required more passes through the drawing dies than 0 gauge wire did.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] Manufacturers of wire formerly had proprietary wire gauge systems; the development of standardized wire gauges rationalized selection of wire for a particular purpose.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] While the AWG is essentially identical to the Brown & Sharpe (B&S) sheet metal gauge, the B&S gauge was designed for use with sheet metals.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] These are functionally interchangeable, but the use of B&S in relation to wire gauges, rather than sheet metal gauges, is technically improper.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] Increasing gauge numbers denote logarithmically decreasing wire diameters, which is similar to many other non-metric gauging systems such as British Standard Wire Gauge (SWG).
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] However, AWG is dissimilar to IEC 60228, the metric wire-size standard used in most parts of the world, based directly on the wire cross-section area (in square millimetres, mm2).
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] The AWG tables are for a single, solid and round conductor.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] The AWG of a stranded wire is determined by the cross-sectional area of the equivalent solid conductor.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] Because there are also small gaps between the strands, a stranded wire will always have a slightly larger overall diameter than a solid wire with the same AWG.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] By definition, 36 AWG is 0.005 inches in diameter, and 0000 AWG is 0.46 inches (11.68 mm) in diameter.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] The ratio of these diameters is 1:92, and there are 40 gauge sizes from 36 to 0000, or 39 steps.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] Because each successive gauge number increases cross sectional area by a constant multiple, diameters vary geometrically.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] Any two successive gauges (e.g., *A* and *B*) have diameters whose ratio (dia.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] Similarly for gauges *n* steps apart, the diameter ratio of the first to last gauges is about 1.1229*n*.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] Where *n* is the AWG size for gauges from 36 to 0.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] The standard ASTM B258-02 (2008), *Standard Specification for Standard Nominal Diameters and Cross-Sectional Areas of AWG Sizes of Solid Round Wires Used as Electrical Conductors*, defines the ratio between successive sizes to be the 39th root of 92, or approximately 1.1229.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] ASTM B258-02 also dictates that wire diameters should be tabulated with no more than 4 significant figures, with a resolution of no more than 0.0001 inches (0.1 mils) for wires thicker than 44 AWG, and 0.00001 inches (0.01 mils) for wires 45 AWG and thinner.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] Sizes with multiple zeros are successively thicker than 0 AWG and can be denoted using "*number of zeros*/0", for example 4/0 AWG for 0000 AWG.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] For an m/0 AWG wire, use *n* = −(*m* − 1) = 1 − *m* in the above formulas.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] The table below shows various data including both the resistance of the various wire gauges and the allowable current (ampacity) based on a copper conductor with plastic insulation.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] The diameter information in the table applies to *solid* wires.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] Stranded wires are calculated by calculating the equivalent cross sectional copper wire area.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] Fusing current (melting wire) is estimated based on 25 °C (77 °F) ambient temperature.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] The table below assumes DC, or AC frequencies equal to or less than 60 Hz, and does not take skin effect into account.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] "Turns of wire per unit length" refers to wire wound in a helix with the turns touching, as in a solenoid and is therefore the reciprocal of the conductor diameter.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] As wire in such a coil normally has insulation, this figure forms an upper bound.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] In the North American electrical industry, conductors thicker than 4/0 AWG are generally identified by the area in thousands of circular mils (kcmil), where 1 kcmil = 0.5067 mm2.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] The next wire size thicker than 4/0 has a cross section of 250 kcmil.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] A *circular mil* is the area of a wire one mil in diameter.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] One million circular mils is the area of a circle with 1,000 mil (1 inch) diameter.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] An older abbreviation for one thousand circular mils is *MCM*.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] AWG can also be used to describe stranded wire.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] The AWG size of a stranded wire represents the sum of the cross-sectional diameter of the individual strands; the gaps between strands are not counted.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] When made with circular strands, these gaps occupy about 25% of the wire area, thus requiring the overall bundle diameter to be about 13% larger than a solid wire of equal gauge.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] Stranded wires are specified with three numbers, the overall AWG size, the number of strands, and the AWG size of a strand.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] The number of strands and the AWG size of a strand are separated by a slash.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] For example, a 22 AWG 7/30 stranded wire is a 22 AWG wire made from seven strands of 30 AWG wire.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] As indicated in the Formulae and Rules of thumb sections above, differences in AWG size translate directly into ratios of diameter or area.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] This property can be employed to easily find the AWG size of a stranded bundle by measuring the diameter and count of its strands.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] (This only applies to bundles with circular strands of identical size.) To find the AWG size of 7-strand wire with equal strands, subtract 8.4 from the AWG size of a strand.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] Similarly, for 19-strand subtract 12.7, and for 37 subtract 15.6.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] Measuring strand diameter is often easier and more accurate than attempting to measure bundle diameter and packing ratio.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] Such measurement can be done with a wire gauge go-no-go tool or with a caliper or micrometer.
[src:horsepower/american-wire-gauge] Alternative ways are commonly used in the electrical industry to specify wire sizes as AWG.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The term was adopted in the late 18th century by Scottish engineer James Watt to compare the output of steam engines with the power of draft horses.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] It was later expanded to include the output power of other power-generating machinery such as piston engines, turbines, and electric motors.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The definition of the unit varied among geographical regions.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Most countries now use the SI unit watt for measurement of power.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] With the implementation of the EU Directive 80/181/EEC on 1 January 2010, the use of horsepower in the EU is permitted only as a supplementary unit.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The development of the steam engine provided a reason to compare the output of horses with that of the engines that could replace them.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] So that an engine which will raise as much water as two horses, working together at one time in such a work, can do, and for which there must be constantly kept ten or twelve horses for doing the same.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Then I say, such an engine may be made large enough to do the work required in employing eight, ten, fifteen, or twenty horses to be constantly maintained and kept for doing such a work...
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The idea was later used by James Watt to help market the Watt steam engine, an improved Newcomen steam engine.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] He had previously agreed to take royalties of one-third of the savings in coal from the older Newcomen steam engines.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] This royalty scheme did not work with customers who did not have existing steam engines but used horses instead.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Watt determined that a horse could turn a mill wheel 144 times in an hour (or 2.4 times a minute).
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The wheel was 12 feet (3.7 m) in radius; therefore, the horse travelled 2.4 × 2π × 12 feet in one minute.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Watt judged that the horse could pull with a force of 180 pounds-force (800 N).
[src:horsepower/horsepower] A common legend states that the unit was created when one of Watt's first customers, a brewer, specifically demanded an engine that would match a horse, and chose the strongest horse he had and driving it to the limit.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] In that legend, Watt accepted the challenge and built a machine that was actually even stronger than the figure achieved by the brewer, and the output of that machine became the horsepower.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Wassersug published correspondence in *Nature* summarizing measurements and calculations of peak and sustained work rates of a horse.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] When considering human-powered equipment, a healthy human can produce about 1.2 hp (0.89 kW) briefly (see orders of magnitude) and sustain about 0.1 hp (0.07 kW) indefinitely; trained athletes can manage up to about 2.5 hp (2 kW) briefly and 0.35 hp (0.26 kW) for a period of several hours.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The Jamaican sprinter Usain Bolt produced a maximum of 3.5 hp (2.6 kW) 0.89 seconds into his 9.58 second 100-metre (109.4 yd) sprint world record in 2009.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] In 2023 a group of engineers modified a dynamometer to be able to measure how much power a horse can produce.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] This horse was measured to 5.7 hp (4.3 kW).
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The constant 5252 is the rounded value of (33,000 ft⋅lbf/min)/(2π rad/rev).
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The various units used to indicate this definition (*PS*, *KM*, *cv*, *hk*, *pk*, *k*, *ks* and *ch*) all translate to *horsepower* in English.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] British manufacturers often intermix metric horsepower and mechanical horsepower depending on the origin of the engine in question.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] DIN 66036 defines one metric horsepower (Pferdestärke, or PS) as the power to raise a mass of 75 kilograms against the Earth's gravitational force over a distance of one metre in one second: 75 kg × 9.80665 m/s2 × 1 m / 1 s = 75 kgf⋅m/s = 1 PS.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] This is equivalent to 735.49875 W, or 98.6% of an imperial horsepower.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] In 1972, the PS was replaced by the kilowatt as the official power-measuring unit in EEC directives.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] 'mechanical horse'), Slovenian *konjska moč (KM)*, the Ukrainian кінська сила (к. с.), the Romanian *cal-putere (CP)*, and the German *Pferdestärke (PS)*.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] In the 19th century, revolutionary-era France had its own unit used to replace the *cheval vapeur* (horsepower); based on a 100 kgf⋅m/s standard, it was called the poncelet and was abbreviated *p*.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Tax, or fiscal, horsepower is a non-linear rating of a motor vehicle for tax purposes.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Tax-horsepower ratings were originally more or less directly related to engine displacements, but, as of 2000, many countries have changed over to systems based on CO2 emissions so the current systems are not directly comparable to old tax horsepower.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The Citroën 2CV is named for its French fiscal horsepower rating, *deux chevaux* (2CV).
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Nameplates on electrical motors show their available shaft power output, not the electrical power input.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] This power output is ordinarily stated in watts or kilowatts.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] In the United States, the power output is stated in horsepower.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] where pressure is in psi and flow rate is in US gallons per minute.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Drilling rigs are powered mechanically by rotating the bit from above.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Hydraulic power is still needed, though, as 1500 to 5000 W are required to push mud through the drill bit to clear waste rock.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Additional hydraulic power may also be used to drive a down-hole mud motor to power directional drilling.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] When using SI units, the equation becomes coherent and there is no dividing constant.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] where pressure is in pascals (Pa), and flow rate is in cubic metres per second (m3).
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Boiler horsepower is a boiler's capacity to deliver steam to a steam engine and is not the same unit of power as the 550 ft⋅lb/s definition.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] One boiler horsepower is equal to the thermal energy rate required to evaporate 34.5 pounds (15.6 kg) of fresh water at 212 °F (100 °C) in one hour.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] In the early days of steam use, the boiler horsepower was roughly comparable to the horsepower of engines fed by the boiler.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The term *boiler horsepower* was originally developed at the Philadelphia Centennial Exhibition in 1876, where the best steam engines of that period were tested.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The average steam consumption of those engines (per output horsepower) was determined to be the evaporation of 30 pounds (14 kg) of water per hour, based on feed water at 100 °F (38 °C), and saturated steam generated at 70 psi (480 kPa).
[src:horsepower/horsepower] This original definition is equivalent to a boiler heat output of 33,485 Btu/h (9.813 kW).
[src:horsepower/horsepower] A few years later in 1884, the ASME redefined the boiler horsepower as the thermal output equal to the evaporation of 34.5 pounds per hour of water "from and at" 212 °F (100 °C).
[src:horsepower/horsepower] This considerably simplified boiler testing, and provided more accurate comparisons of the boilers at that time.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] This revised definition is equivalent to a boiler heat output of 33,469 Btu/h (9.809 kW).
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Present industrial practice is to define *boiler horsepower* as a boiler thermal output equal to 33,475 Btu/h (9.811 kW), which is very close to the original and revised definitions.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Boiler horsepower is still used to measure boiler output in industrial boiler engineering in the US.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Boiler horsepower is abbreviated *BHP*, which is also used in many places to symbolize brake horsepower.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Drawbar power (dbp) is the power a railway locomotive has available to haul a train or an agricultural tractor to pull an implement.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] This is a measured figure rather than a calculated one.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] A special railway car called a dynamometer car coupled behind a locomotive keeps a continuous record of drawbar tension and speed.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] From these, the power generated can be calculated.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] To determine the maximum power available, a controllable load is required; it is normally a second locomotive with its brakes applied, in addition to a static load.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Example: How much power is needed to pull a drawbar load of 2,025 pounds-force at 5 miles per hour?
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The constant 375 is because 1 hp = 375 lbf⋅mph.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] If other units are used, the constant is different.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] When using coherent SI units (watts, newtons, and metres per second), no constant is needed, and the formula becomes *P* = *Fv*.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] This formula may also be used to calculate the power of a jet engine, using the speed of the jet and the thrust required to maintain that speed.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Example: how much power is generated with a thrust of 4000 pounds at 400 miles per hour?
[src:horsepower/horsepower] This measure was instituted by the Royal Automobile Club and was used to denote the power of early 20th-century British cars.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Many cars took their names from this figure (hence the Austin Seven and Riley Nine), while others had names such as "40/50 hp", which indicated the RAC figure followed by the true measured power.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Taxable horsepower does not reflect developed horsepower; rather, it is a calculated figure based on the engine's bore size, number of cylinders, and a (now archaic) presumption of engine efficiency.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] As new engines were designed with ever-increasing efficiency, it was no longer a useful measure, but was kept in use by UK regulations, which used the rating for tax purposes.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The United Kingdom was not the only country that used the RAC rating; many states in Australia used RAC hp to determine taxation.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The RAC formula was sometimes applied in British colonies as well, such as Kenya (British East Africa).
[src:horsepower/horsepower] See, for example, the early Chrysler Hemi engine.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The power of an engine may be measured or estimated at several points in the transmission of the power from its generation to its application.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] A number of names are used for the power developed at various stages in this process, but none is a clear indicator of either the measurement system or definition used.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] shaft horsepower minus frictional losses in the universal joint/s, differential, wheel bearings, tire and chain, (if present).
[src:horsepower/horsepower] All the above assumes that no power inflation factors have been applied to any of the readings.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Engine designers use expressions other than horsepower to denote objective targets or performance, such as brake mean effective pressure (BMEP).
[src:horsepower/horsepower] This is a coefficient of theoretical brake horsepower and cylinder pressures during combustion.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Nominal horsepower (nhp) is an early 19th-century rule of thumb used to estimate the power of steam engines.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] It assumed a steam pressure of 7 psi (48 kPa).
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Nominal horsepower = 7 × area of piston in square inches × equivalent piston speed in feet per minute/33,000.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] For paddle ships, the Admiralty rule was that the piston speed in feet per minute was taken as 129.7 × (stroke)1/3.38.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] For screw steamers, the intended piston speed was used.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The stroke (or length of stroke) was the distance moved by the piston measured in feet.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] For the nominal horsepower to equal the actual power it would be necessary for the mean steam pressure in the cylinder during the stroke to be 7 psi (48 kPa) and for the piston speed to be that generated by the assumed relationship for paddle ships.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The French Navy used the same definition of nominal horsepower as the Royal Navy.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Indicated horsepower (ihp) is the theoretical power of a reciprocating engine if it is completely frictionless in converting the expanding gas energy (piston pressure × displacement) in the cylinders.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] It is calculated from the pressures developed in the cylinders, measured by a device called an *engine indicator* – hence indicated horsepower.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] As the piston advances throughout its stroke, the pressure against the piston generally decreases, and the indicator device usually generates a graph of pressure vs stroke within the working cylinder.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] From this graph the amount of work performed during the piston stroke may be calculated.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Indicated horsepower was a better measure of engine power than nominal horsepower (nhp) because it took account of steam pressure.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] But unlike later measures such as shaft horsepower (shp) and brake horsepower (bhp), it did not take into account power losses due to the machinery internal frictional losses, such as a piston sliding within the cylinder, plus bearing friction, transmission and gear box friction, etc.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] In Europe, the DIN 70020 standard tests the engine fitted with all ancillaries and the exhaust system as used in the car.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The older American standard (SAE gross horsepower, referred to as *bhp*) used an engine without alternator, water pump, and other auxiliary components such as power steering pump, muffled exhaust system, etc., so the figures were higher than the European figures for the same engine.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The newer American standard (referred to as *SAE net horsepower*) tests an engine with all the auxiliary components (detailed in Engine power test standards).
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Shaft horsepower (shp) is the power delivered to a propeller or turbine shaft.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Shaft horsepower is a common rating for turboshaft and turboprop engines, industrial turbines, and some marine applications.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Equivalent shaft horsepower (eshp) is sometimes used to rate turboprop engines.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] It includes the equivalent power derived from residual jet thrust from the turbine exhaust.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] 2.5 pounds-force (11 N) of residual jet thrust is estimated to be produced from one unit of horsepower.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] There exist a number of different standards determining how the power and torque of an automobile engine is measured and corrected.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Correction factors are used to adjust power and torque measurements to standard atmospheric conditions, to provide a more accurate comparison between engines as they are affected by the pressure, humidity, and temperature of ambient air.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] In the early twentieth century, a so-called "SAE horsepower" was sometimes quoted for U.S. automobiles.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] This long predates the Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE) horsepower measurement standards and was another name for the industry standard ALAM or NACC horsepower figure and the same as the British RAC horsepower also used for tax purposes.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Alliance for Automotive Innovation is the current successor of ALAM and NACC.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] This contrasts with both SAE net power and DIN 70020 standards, which account for engine accessories (but not transmission losses).
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The atmospheric correction standards for barometric pressure, humidity and temperature for SAE gross power testing were relatively idealistic.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] In the United States, the term *bhp* fell into disuse in 1971–1972, as automakers began to quote power in terms of SAE net horsepower in accord with SAE standard J1349.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Like SAE gross and other brake horsepower protocols, SAE net hp is measured at the engine's crankshaft, and so does not account for transmission losses.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] However, similar to the DIN 70020 standard, SAE net power testing protocol calls for standard production-type belt-driven accessories, air cleaner, emission controls, exhaust system, and other power-consuming accessories.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] This produces ratings in closer alignment with the power produced by the engine as it is actually configured and sold.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] In 2005, the SAE introduced "SAE Certified Power" with SAE J2723.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] To attain certification the test must follow the SAE standard in question, take place in an ISO 9000/9002 certified facility and be witnessed by an SAE approved third party.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] A few manufacturers such as Honda and Toyota switched to the new ratings immediately.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The rating for the Toyota Camry 3.0 L *1MZ-FE* V6 fell from 210 to 190 hp (157 to 142 kW).
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The company's Lexus ES 330 and Camry SE V6 were previously rated at 225 hp (168 kW) but the ES 330 dropped to 218 hp (163 kW) while the Camry declined to 210 hp (157 kW).
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The first engine certified under the new program was the 7.0-litre LS7 used in the 2006 Chevrolet Corvette Z06.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Certified power rose slightly from 500 to 505 hp (373 to 377 kW).
[src:horsepower/horsepower] While Toyota and Honda are retesting their entire vehicle lineups, other automakers generally are retesting only those with updated powertrains.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] For example, the 2006 Ford Five Hundred is rated at 203 hp (151 kW), the same as that of 2005 model.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] However, the 2006 rating does not reflect the new SAE testing procedure, as Ford did not opt to incur the extra expense of retesting its existing engines.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Over time, most automakers are expected to comply with the new guidelines.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] SAE tightened its horsepower rules to eliminate the opportunity for engine manufacturers to manipulate factors affecting performance such as how much oil was in the crankcase, engine control system calibration, and whether an engine was tested with high octane fuel.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] In some cases, such can add up to a change in horsepower ratings.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] DIN 70020 is a German DIN standard for measuring road vehicle horsepower.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] DIN hp is measured at the engine's output shaft as a form of metric horsepower rather than mechanical horsepower.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] Similar to SAE net power rating, and unlike SAE gross power, DIN testing measures the engine as installed in the vehicle, with cooling system, charging system and stock exhaust system all connected.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] DIN hp is often abbreviated as "PS", derived from the German word ***Pferdestärke*** (literally, "horse strength").
[src:horsepower/horsepower] A test standard by Italian CUNA (*Commissione Tecnica per l'Unificazione nell'Automobile*, Technical Commission for Automobile Unification), a federated entity of standards organisation UNI, was formerly used in Italy.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] CUNA prescribed that the engine be tested with all accessories necessary to its running fitted (such as the water pump), while all others – such as alternator/dynamo, radiator fan, and exhaust manifold – could be omitted.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] All calibration and accessories had to be as on production engines.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] ECE R24 is a UN standard for the approval of compression ignition engine emissions, installation and measurement of engine power.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] It is similar to DIN 70020 standard, but with different requirements for connecting an engine's fan during testing causing it to absorb less power from the engine.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] ECE R85 is a UN standard for the approval of internal combustion engines with regard to the measurement of the net power.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] 80/1269/EEC of 16 December 1980 is a European Union standard for road vehicle engine power.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) publishes several standards for measuring engine horsepower.
[src:horsepower/horsepower] JIS D 1001 is a Japanese net, and gross, engine power test code for automobiles or trucks having a spark ignition, diesel engine, or fuel injection engine.
